nd change. Bradbury draws on a wealth of primary sources, weaving together biographies of individual women against a backdrop of the collective genealogies of over 500 , to show how women � Catholic, Protestant, and Jewish, wealthy and working-class � interacted with and shaped the city's culture, customs, and institutions, even as they laboured under the shifting conditions of patriarchy. A truly monumental study, Wife to Widow is an immensely readable, rigorous, and compelling examination of the significance of marriage and widowhood at a key moment in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFemmes mariéesxConditions socialesx19e sièclexQuébec (Province)xMontréal. 0aFemmes mariéesxDroitxHistoirex19e sièclexQuébec (Province). 0aMarried women -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- Québec (Province) -- History -- 19th century. 0aMarried women -- Québec (Province) -- Montréal -- Social conditions -- 19th century. 0aMarried womenxLegal status, laws, etcxHistoryx19th centuryxQuébec (Province). 0aMarried womenxSocial conditionsx19th centuryxQuébec (Province)xMontréal. 0aMontréal (Québec) -- Biography. 0aMontréal (Québec) -- History -- 19th century. 0aVeuvesxConditions socialesx19e sièclexQuébec (Province)xMontréal. 0aVeuvesxDroitxHistoirex19e sièclexQuébec (Province). 0aWidows -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- Québec (Province) -- History -- 19th century. 0aWidows -- Québec (Province) -- Montréal -- Social conditions -- 19th century. 0aWidowsxLegal status, laws, etcxHistoryx19th centuryxQuébec (Province). 0aWidowsxSocial conditionsx19th centuryxQuébec (Province)xMontréal. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter